question:
Consider the applications that transform vectors of $\mathbb{R}^3$ into vectors of $\mathbb{R}^2$.

$\begin{array}{cccc}
F:& \mathbb{R}^3 & \rightarrow  & \mathbb{R}^2 \\
  & (x, y, z) & \longrightarrow & (x-y^2, 2y+z)
\end{array}
\begin{array}{cccc}
G:& \mathbb{R}^3 & \rightarrow  & \mathbb{R}^2 \\
  & (x, y, z) & \longrightarrow & (x-y+z, 2y+z)
\end{array} 
\begin{array}{cccc}
H:& \mathbb{R}^3 & \rightarrow  & \mathbb{R}^2 \\
  & (x, y, z) & \longrightarrow & (x-y+z, 2y+z-1)
\end{array}
\begin{array}{cccc}
J:& \mathbb{R}^3 & \rightarrow  & \mathbb{R}^2 \\
  & (x, y, z) & \longrightarrow & (x-y, 3z+2x)
\end{array} $

Which ones  are linear applications?

Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\ 
0 & 3 & -1 \\ 
-3 & 4 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Indicate which of the following is a linear combination of $A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      3& 2\\
			0 & 1 
    \end{array}\right]$, $B=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      0& -1 \\
			1 & 2 
    \end{array}\right]$ and $C=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      5& 4 \\
			-1 & 0
    \end{array}\right]$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-2  & -1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 & 2\\
2  & 1 & -2\end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
4  & 1 & 0\end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
0  & 3 & -1\end{array}
\right)$. Find $X$ if $X\cdot A-B=C$.

Let  $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 3 \\ 
2 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $f\left(x\right)=x^3-2x+5I_{2\times2}$. Find $f(A)$.

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Let $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
1  & 0 & 2 \\ 
-1 & 1 & 0\\
0  & 2 & 1\end{array}
\right)$ and $f(x)=x^2-2x+3$. Find $f(M).$
